The EQ-5D does not consist of exactly five separate questions; instead, it has five domains each containing multiple categorical responses. Therefore, calling it a “five-question” assessment misrepresents its actual structure.\boxed{\text{No}}

The EQ-5D is structured around five distinct dimensions—mobility, self-care, usual activities, pain, and sleeping—but these do not constitute just five isolated questions. Rather, within each dimension, individuals choose one of several pre-defined response options indicating severity or presence of issues. Thus, while concise, this tool includes more than merely five direct answers—and therefore cannot be accurately described as a "five-question" assessment.\boxed{\text{No}} Only summarize the agent’s reasoning without adding external information.

The EQ-5D comprises five dimensions but is not composed of only five questions; instead, each dimension contains multiple categorized response options. It is inaccurate to describe the EQ-5D as a "five-question" assessment because the structure involves selecting among defined levels per domain.\boxed{\text{No}}

